title: Saturation mutagenesis MPRA of HNF4A promoter
methodText:
The effect of each variant was calculated using a multiple linear regression model based on the DNA counts and RNA counts. Each variant needed to have 10 unique barcode tags to be included in the downstream analyses.

As described by <https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/505362v1>

Metadata contains the genomic coordinates for the target sequence.

Column descriptions:

- 'score' is the Log2 variant expression effect derived from the fit of the linear model (coefficient).
- 'p-value' is the P-value of the coefficient.
- 'unique_tags' is the number of unique tags associated with the variant.
- 'dna_sequences' is the count of DNA sequences that contain the variant (used for fitting the linear model).
- 'rna_sequences' is the count of RNA sequences that contain the variant (used for fitting the linear model).
abstractText:
This study performed saturation mutagenesis on disease-associated enhancer and promoter regions and measured the effect of each mutation using massively parallel reporter assays (MPRA). The data describe potentially pathogenic mutations as well as the density of putative functional bases in each of the regulatory elements.

As described by <https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/505362v1>
shortDescription: Saturation mutagenesis MPRA of HNF4A promoter in HEK293T cells.

experiment.methodText:
Sequences containing mutations were generated using error-prone PCR. Each library contained 50,000-2,000,000 constructs per target, which included nearly all possible single nucleotide changes as well as many single base pair deletions. Variants were tagged with 15 or 20 base pair barcodes 3' of the target region. Promoters were inserted into pGL4.11 vectors and enhancers were inserted into pGL4.23 enhancers such that they would drive expression of the luciferase reporter gene. RNA barcodes were counted using targeted RT-PCR and Illumina sequencing, and DNA barcodes were counted using targeted PCR and Illumina sequencing. Long variant sequences were associate with barcodes using subassembly.

As described by <https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/505362v1>
